  <h1>TGS Flow Pilot</h1>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>TGS Flow enables two capabilities:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Generate Jira compliant backlog items from planning artifacts</li>
    <li>Automatically reconcile GitHub engineering activity back into Jira so work in progress reflects real execution</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This pilot validates the workflow end to end before expanding usage across CORE.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Pilot Goals</h2>
  <p>The pilot will validate that teams can:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Generate backlog items from requirements, solution docs, or meeting notes</li>
    <li>Assign engineering work through those backlog items</li>
    <li>Automatically update Jira based on GitHub activity</li>
    <li>Reduce manual Jira updates</li>
    <li>Improve visibility into real engineering work</li>
  </ul>

  <hr />

  <h2>Pilot Scope</h2>

  <h3>Path A: TGS Flow VS Code Extension</h3>
  <p>Teams use the TGS Flow repository and VS Code extension to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Generate backlog items</li>
    <li>Reconcile GitHub commits with Jira work</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Path B: Claude Jira CLI</h3>
  <p>Some participants may use the Claude Jira CLI integration being piloted by R2E.</p>
  <p>Questions related to the CLI workflow should be directed to the CLI support lead.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>Pilot Timeline</h2>

  <h3>Sprint 1: Onboarding and Validation</h3>
  <p><span class="meta">Dates:</span> March 19 to April 1</p>
  <p><span class="meta">Objective:</span> Each participant and their team installs the tooling and validates the workflow.</p>

  <p><span class="meta">Expected Outcomes</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Install and configure tooling</li>
    <li>Run an initial workflow test</li>
    <li>Identify the real use case that will run in Sprint 2</li>
    <li>Confirm which engineers must participate</li>
    <li>Validate the workflow works end to end</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Sprint 1 Test Definition</h3>
  <p>Each participant must run a small validation test to confirm the workflow works before participating in Sprint 2.</p>
  <p>The purpose of the test is to validate:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Tool installation</li>
    <li>Backlog generation</li>
    <li>Jira integration</li>
    <li>Team access setup</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The test should create a minimal amount of Jira content.</p>

  <h4>Required Test Scope</h4>
  <p>The test should generate only:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>1 Epic</li>
    <li>1 Story</li>
  </ul>
  <p>These should be created from a simple test document or notes.</p>
  <p>Example source artifact:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Short solution note</li>
    <li>Small design outline</li>
    <li>Meeting notes</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The goal is to validate that the workflow works, not to generate real backlog.</p>

  <h4>Test Steps</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>Install and configure the tool</li>
    <li>Generate backlog from a simple source document</li>
    <li>Confirm the Epic and Story are created in Jira</li>
    <li>Verify the tickets contain expected fields</li>
    <li>Confirm the participant has access to assign work</li>
    <li>Define the real use case that will be executed in Sprint 2</li>
    <li>Confirm the engineers required for the Sprint 2 use case</li>
    <li>Ensure those engineers complete setup if they will participate</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Test Data Cleanup Requirement</h3>
  <p>The Sprint 1 test should create minimal Jira content.</p>
  <div class="warning">
    <p><strong>To avoid cluttering Jira projects:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Only create 1 Epic and 1 Story</li>
      <li>Use a clearly identifiable naming pattern</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>Example naming convention:</p>
  <pre>[TGS TEST] Example Backlog Generation</pre>

  <p>After the test is completed:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Participants should notify the pilot admins in Slack</li>
    <li>Pilot admins will remove the test artifacts</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Note: Not all participants will have permission to delete Jira issues. If cleanup is required, pilot administrators will handle deletion.</p>
  <p>The purpose of this process is to prevent Jira hygiene issues during the pilot.</p>

  <h3>Sprint 2: Real Use Case Execution</h3>
  <p><span class="meta">Dates:</span> April 2 to April 15</p>
  <p><span class="meta">Objective:</span> Each team runs one real engineering use case through the workflow.</p>

  <p><span class="meta">Expected Outcomes</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use a real requirements artifact or solution document</li>
    <li>Generate backlog items</li>
    <li>Assign work to engineers</li>
    <li>Execute the work</li>
    <li>Validate that GitHub activity updates Jira</li>
    <li>Provide feedback on workflow gaps or friction</li>
  </ul>

  <p><span class="meta">Sprint 2 Demonstration</span></p>
  <p>At the end of the sprint each team should show:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Source artifact used</li>
    <li>Generated backlog</li>
    <li>Jira tickets created</li>
    <li>Engineers assigned</li>
    <li>Jira updates during execution</li>
    <li>Feedback and improvement suggestions</li>
  </ul>

  <hr />

  <h2>What Participants Need To Do</h2>

  <h3>During Sprint 1</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Review this documentation</li>
    <li>Access the TGS Flow repository</li>
    <li>Install and configure the tool</li>
    <li>Run the Sprint 1 validation test</li>
    <li>Define the real use case for Sprint 2</li>
    <li>Identify engineers who must participate</li>
    <li>Ensure those engineers complete setup</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>During Sprint 2</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Execute a real use case</li>
    <li>Generate backlog items</li>
    <li>Assign work through Jira</li>
    <li>Execute work through the sprint</li>
    <li>Validate GitHub to Jira updates</li>
    <li>Provide feedback</li>
  </ol>

